sease)|plague]] | <ref name="Practitioner">{{cite book|title=Practitioner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cWUCAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=29 March 2011|year=1877}}</ref> |- | 4,737 | [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] | 1853 | [[Cholera epidemic of Copenhagen 1853]] | [[cholera]] | <ref>[http://wayback-01.kb.dk/wayback/20100504134515/http://www2.kb.dk/udstillinger/medhist/kolera/efterhistorien.html] About Cholera epidemic of Copenhagen 1853</ref> |- | 616 | [[England]] | 1854 | [[Broad Street cholera outbreak]] | [[cholera]] | <ref name="Snow1855">{{cite book|author=John Snow|title=On the mode of communication of cholera|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-N0_AAAAcAAJ|accessdate=29 March 2011|year=1855|publisher=John Churchill}}</ref> |- | | [[United States]] | 1855 | | [[yellow fever]] | |- | | worldwide | 1855–1960 | [[Third plague pandemic]] | [[bubonic plague]] | <ref name=Pryor/> |- | | [[Portugal]] | 1857 | [[Lisbon]] | [[yellow fever]] | |- | | [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia | 1857 | | [[smallpox]] | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicalpioneers.com/colonial.htm|title=Australian Medical Pioneers Index (AMPI) – Colonial Medical Life|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> |- | | [[Europe]], [[North America]], [[South America]] | 1857–1859 | | [[influenza]] | <ref>Beveridge, W.I.B. Influenza, the Last Great Plague (Heinemann, London, 1977){{Page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> |- | | [[Middle East]] | 1863–1879 | [[fourth cholera pandemic]] | [[cholera]] | <ref name=Hays2005/> |- | | [[Egypt]] | 1865 | | [[cholera]] | <ref name=Kuhnke /><ref name=Gallagher/> |- | | [[Russia]], [[Germany]] | 1866–1867 | | [[cholera]] | |- | | [[Australia]] | 1867 | [[Sydney]] | [[measles]] | |- | | [[Iraq]] | 1867 | | [[Plague (disease)|plague]] | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1902encyclopedia.com/P/PLA/plague-13.html|title=1902Encyclopedia.com|publisher=|accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref> |- | | [[Argentina]] | 1852–1871 | [[Buenos Aires]] | [[Yellow Fever in Buenos Aires|yellow fever]] | <ref name=Persona>Cited in: Howlin, Diego (2004). [http://www.revistapersona.com.ar/Persona34/34DHowlin.htm "Vómito Negro, Historia de la fiebre amarilla, en Buenos Aires de 1871"], ''Revista Persona''.</ref> |- | | [[Germany]] | 1870–1871 | | [[smallpox]] | |- | 40,000 | [[Fiji]] | 1875 | [[Fiji]] | [[measles]] | <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000081/18750929/038/0007|title=Death of Forty Thousand Fijians from Measles|date=29 Sep 1875|publisher=Liverpool Mercury|accessdate=9 Nov 2012}}</ref> |- | | [[Russian Empire]] | 1877 | [[Baku]], now part of [[Azerbaijan]] | [[Plague (disease)|plague]] | <ref name="1911e" /> |- | | [[Egypt]] | 1881 | | [[cholera]] | <ref name=Kuhnke /><ref name=Gallagher/> |- | >&nbsp;9,000 | [[India]], [[Germany]] | 1881–1896 | [[fifth cholera pandemic]] | [[cholera]] | <ref name=Hays2005/> |- | 3,164 | [[Montreal]] | 1885 | | [[smallpox]] | [[Timeline of Montreal history#1880s|timeline]] |- | 1,000,000 | worldwide | 1889–1890 | [[1889–1890 flu pandemic]] | [[influenza]] | <ref name="Board1893">{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Local Government Board|title=Further report and papers on epidemic influenza, 1889–92: with an introduction by the medical officer of the Local Government Board|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OAUTAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 March 2011|year=1893|publisher=Eyre}}{{Page needed|date=July 2013}}</ref> |}
